lf, H. Rider Haggard, Bram Stoker, Rudyard Kipling, and Joseph Conrad. Demonstrating the investment of modernist writing in the problems of geopolitics and in the public discourse of time, Barrows argues that it is possible, and productive, to rethink the politics of modernism through the politics of time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEnglish fictionxHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aEnglish fictionxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)xEnglish-speaking countries. 0aModernism (Literature)zEnglish-speaking countries. 0aTime in literature. 0aTimexPolitical aspects. 0aTimexSystems and standardsxEnglish-speaking countries. 0aTimexSystems and standards. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520948150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520948150.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles